PGREP(1)                              User Commands                             PGREP(1)

NNAAMMEE
       pgrep, pkill - look up or signal processes based on name and other attributes

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       ppggrreepp [options] pattern
       ppkkiillll [options] pattern

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       ppggrreepp  looks  through  the  currently running processes and lists the process IDs
       which match the selection criteria to stdout.  All the criteria  have  to  match.
       For example,

              $ pgrep -u root sshd

       will only list the processes called sssshhdd AND owned by rroooott.  On the other hand,

              $ pgrep -u root,daemon

       will list the processes owned by rroooott OR ddaaeemmoonn.

       ppkkiillll will send the specified signal (by default SSIIGGTTEERRMM) to each process instead
       of listing them on stdout.

OOPPTTIIOONNSS
       --_s_i_g_n_a_l
       ----ssiiggnnaall _s_i_g_n_a_l
              Defines the signal to send to each matched process.  Either the numeric or
              the symbolic signal name can be used.  (ppkkiillll only.)

       --cc, ----ccoouunntt
              Suppress normal output; instead print a count of matching processes.  When
              count does not match anything, e.g. returns zero, the command will  return
              non-zero value.

       --dd, ----ddeelliimmiitteerr _d_e_l_i_m_i_t_e_r
              Sets  the string used to delimit each process ID in the output (by default
              a newline).  (ppggrreepp only.)

       --ff, ----ffuullll
              The _p_a_t_t_e_r_n is normally only matched against the process name.  When --ff is
              set, the full command line is used.

       --gg, ----ppggrroouupp _p_g_r_p,...
              Only  match processes in the process group IDs listed.  Process group 0 is
              translated into ppggrreepp's or ppkkiillll's own process group.

       --GG, ----ggrroouupp _g_i_d,...
              Only match processes whose real group ID is listed.  Either the  numerical
              or symbolical value may be used.

       --ii, ----iiggnnoorree--ccaassee
              Match processes case-insensitively.

       --ll, ----lliisstt--nnaammee
              List the process name as well as the process ID.  (ppggrreepp only.)

       --aa, ----lliisstt--ffuullll
              List the full command line as well as the process ID.  (ppggrreepp only.)

       --nn, ----nneewweesstt
              Select only the newest (most recently started) of the matching processes.

       --oo, ----oollddeesstt
              Select only the oldest (least recently started) of the matching processes.

       --PP, ----ppaarreenntt _p_p_i_d,...
              Only match processes whose parent process ID is listed.

       --ss, ----sseessssiioonn _s_i_d,...
              Only  match processes whose process session ID is listed.  Session ID 0 is
              translated into ppggrreepp's or ppkkiillll's own session ID.

       --tt, ----tteerrmmiinnaall _t_e_r_m,...
              Only match processes whose controlling terminal is listed.   The  terminal
              name should be specified without the "/dev/" prefix.

       --uu, ----eeuuiidd _e_u_i_d,...
              Only match processes whose effective user ID is listed.  Either the numer‐
              ical or symbolical value may be used.

       --UU, ----uuiidd _u_i_d,...
              Only match processes whose real user ID is listed.  Either  the  numerical
              or symbolical value may be used.

       --vv, ----iinnvveerrssee
              Negates the matching.  This option is usually used in ppggrreepp's context.  In
              ppkkiillll's context the short option is disabled to avoid accidental usage  of
              the option.

       --ww, ----lliigghhttwweeiigghhtt
              Shows  all thread ids instead of pids in ppggrreepp's context.  In ppkkiillll's con‐
              text this option is disabled.

       --xx, ----eexxaacctt
              Only match processes whose names (or command line if -f is specified)  eexx‐‐
              aaccttllyy match the _p_a_t_t_e_r_n.

       --FF, ----ppiiddffiillee _f_i_l_e
              Read  _P_I_D's  from file.  This option is perhaps more useful for ppkkiillll than
              ppggrreepp.

       --LL, ----llooggppiiddffiillee
              Fail if pidfile (see -F) not locked.

       --rr, ----rruunnssttaatteess _D_,_R_,_S_,_Z_,...
              Match only processes which match the process state.

       ----nnss _p_i_d
              Match processes that belong to the same namespaces.  Required  to  run  as
              root  to  match  processes from other users. See --nslist for how to limit
              which namespaces to match.

       ----nnsslliisstt _n_a_m_e,,......
              Match only the provided namespaces. Available namespaces: ipc,  mnt,  net,
              pid, user,uts.

       --VV, ----vveerrssiioonn
              Display version information and exit.

       --hh, ----hheellpp
              Display help and exit.

OOPPEERRAANNDDSS
       _p_a_t_t_e_r_n
              Specifies  an Extended Regular Expression for matching against the process
              names or command lines.

EEXXAAMMPPLLEESS
       Example 1: Find the process ID of the nnaammeedd daemon:

              $ pgrep -u root named

       Example 2: Make ssyysslloogg reread its configuration file:

              $ pkill -HUP syslogd

       Example 3: Give detailed information on all xxtteerrmm processes:

              $ ps -fp $(pgrep -d, -x xterm)

       Example 4: Make all cchhrroommee processes run nicer:

              $ renice +4 $(pgrep chrome)

EEXXIITT SSTTAATTUUSS
       0      One or more processes matched the criteria. For  pkill  the  process  must
              also have been successfully signalled.
       1      No processes matched or none of them could be signalled.
       2      Syntax error in the command line.
       3      Fatal error: out of memory etc.

NNOOTTEESS
       The process name used for matching is limited to the 15 characters present in the
       output of /proc/_p_i_d/stat.  Use the -f option to match against the  complete  com‐
       mand line, /proc/_p_i_d/cmdline.

       The running ppggrreepp or ppkkiillll process will never report itself as a match.

BBUUGGSS
       The  options --nn and --oo and --vv can not be combined.  Let me know if you need to do
       this.

       Defunct processes are reported.

SSEEEE AALLSSOO
       ppss(1), rreeggeexx(7), ssiiggnnaall(7), kkiillllaallll(1), sskkiillll(1), kkiillll(1), kkiillll(2)

